  "analysis": "Across 2026-02-10 to 2026-02-16, spend totaled $128,560.93 against $131,410.15 in revenue, for a very slim overall margin (ROI 2.22%). Performance deteriorated as the week progressed: ROI fell from 16.52% (2/10) and 13.25% (2/11) to 6.05% (2/12) and 3.20% (2/13), then broke sharply negative on 2/14 (spend $24,494.47 vs revenue $17,626.84; ROI -28.04%). Spend was front-loaded midweek (peak spend $28,914.71 on 2/12), but the revenue-to-spend relationship weakened noticeably after 2/12, suggesting either fatigue, targeting/auction pressure, or conversion rate/AOV degradation into the weekend.\n\nTopic + bid-strategy winners were concentrated in ROAS Value campaigns, albeit on very small spend: longsleevecroptops + roas val delivered 250.74% ROI on $10.09 spend (3 results), birthdaypresents + roas val delivered 138.54% ROI on $33.29 (18 results), and bestvacuumdeals + roas val delivered 106.64% ROI on $52.12 (11 results). The biggest losers were also skewed toward roas val and max num pockets: datenightstyle + roas val (-100% ROI on $11.66), healthykitchenlifestyle + roas val (-97.73% on $15.89), slowcookingtools + max val (-94.87% on $17.36), and longsleevecroptops + max num (-94.64% on $26.50). At the strategy level, bid cap was the only clearly positive bucket (ROI 10.45% on $13,118.44 spend; $14,489.40 revenue). Max val was near break-even (ROI -0.87% on $42,192.56), cost cap was slightly negative (ROI -3.08% on $37,215.58), and max num was the weakest at scale (ROI -9.95% on $27,004.40).\n\nNext week, protect profitability by shifting incremental budget toward bid cap (best current scaled ROI at 10.45%) and the best-performing roas val topics, but only after validating with higher spend (the top “winners” are not yet statistically meaningful given $10–$52 spend). Pause or tightly cap the worst combinations immediately (datenightstyle + roas val, healthykitchenlifestyle + roas val, longsleevecroptops + max num, slowcookingtools + max val) and audit 2/14 specifically (tracking, site issues, offer changes, or audience overlap) since it drove the week’s biggest profit compression. Testing priorities: (1) re-run roas val with stricter exclusions/cleaner audiences to see if we can replicate high-ROI pockets at $200–$500/day per topic, (2) creative/landing page refresh ahead of the late-week drop, and (3) bid/CPA guardrails on max num (given -9.95% ROI) so volume doesn’t come at a margin loss.\n\nWeek-over-week, spend increased by $11,124.77 (+9.47%) while revenue was essentially flat (+$9.66, +0.01%), which drove a large ROI deterioration: ROI pct declined by 9.67 percentage points (-81.33%). Efficiency also weakened materially: CPC rose by $0.17 (+94.44%) and CPR rose by $0.97 (+44.5%), while clicks fell by 283,225 (-43.82%) and results fell by 13,073 (-24.26%) despite impressions increasing by 1,479,797 (+13.09%). By strategy, max val scaled hardest (spend +$21,248.50, +101.45%) with a slight ROI improvement (+0.81 pp) but still near break-even (-0.87% ROI), while max num scaled (spend +$11,709.82, +76.56%) and improved ROI by +9.85 pp yet remained negative (-9.95%). The most concerning regression is roas val: spend fell (-$5,997.55, -39.91%) but revenue fell even more (-$13,464.52, -59.35%) and ROI dropped by 48.83 pp (to 2.15%), indicating that what’s left in roas val is far less efficient than last week and needs re-selection/rebuild rather than simple scaling."
